This section presents two example ``sentences for sustainability'' related to 
land use and urban planning.

\paragraph{Individual+Action+Land Use}
Where you live is a key land-use decision in the sense that it determines how you
relate to all the land around you, mainly through your transportation.
However, how you use your domicile is also important.
How many people in your household? 
How will you use the space around your dwelling?
Will you have a lawn (with or without lawn chemicals) like Figure~\ref{fig:kentucky_bluegrass}?
Will you have a vegetable garden?
Will you grow native plants?
Figure~\ref{fig:gutter_diversion} shows one way of reducing the amount of surface
runoff that flows directly into local waterways.

\paragraph{Individual+Law+Urban Planning}
Get involved in your local zoning board, drain commission, or other local government entity. 
Advocate for local \emph{and} regional solutions. 
Being involved in local politics is one of the best ways to make a difference for 
sustainability.

